RIP derived, O - OSPF derived,\n       C - connected, S - static, B - BGP derived,\n       * - candidate default route, IA - OSPF inter area route,\n       i - IS-IS derived, ia - IS-IS, U - per-user static route,\n       o - on-demand routing, M - mobile, P - periodic downloaded static route,\n       D - EIGRP, EX - EIGRP external, E1 - OSPF external type 1 route,\n       E2 - OSPF external type 2 route, N1 - OSPF NSSA external type 1 route,\n       N2 - OSPF NSSA external type 2 route\n\nGateway of last resort is 10.119.254.240 to network 10.140.0.0\n\nO E2 10.110.0.0 [160/5] via 10.119.254.6, 0:01:00, Ethernet2\nE    10.67.10.0 [200/128] via 10.119.254.244, 0:02:22, Ethernet2\nO E2 10.68.132.0 [160/5] via 10.119.254.6, 0:00:59, Ethernet2\nO E2 10.130.0.0 [160/5] via 10.119.254.6, 0:00:59, Ethernet2\nE    10.128.0.0 [200/128] via 10.119.254.244, 0:02:22, Ethernet2\nE    10.129.0.0 [200/129] via 10.119.254.240, 0:02:22, Ethernet2\nE    10.65.129.0 [200/128] via 10.119.254.244, 0:02:22, Ethernet2\nE    10.10.0.0 [200/128] via 10.119.254.244, 0:02:22, Ethernet2\nE    10.75.139.0 [200/129] via 10.119.254.240, 0:02:23, Ethernet2\nE    10.16.208.0 [200/128] via 10.119.254.244, 0:02:22, Ethernet2\nE    10.84.148.0 [200/129] via 10.119.254.240, 0:02:23, Ethernet2\nE    10.31.223.0 [200/128] via 10.119.254.244, 0:02:22, Ethernet2\nE    10.44.236.0 [200/129] via 10.119.254.240, 0:02:23, Ethernet2\nE    10.141.0.0 [200/129] via 10.119.254.240, 0:02:22, Ethernet2\nE    10.140.0.0 [200/129] via 10.119.254.240, 0:02:23, Ethernet2\n</code></pre>\n', '2018-01-03 10:31:38'),
(7, 'Installation and first configuration steps', 5, '<style>\n  .imgs-wrapper{\n    display: flex;\n    flex-direction: row;\n    margin-bottom: 8px;\n  }\n  img {\n    flex-grow: 1;\n    margin: 2px;\n  }\n  a {\n    outline: none;\n  }\n</style>\n<!--<img src=\"../../../assets/images/00setup.png\" alt=\"Setup\">-->\n<p>Kali Loonix installed and first config steps</p>\n<ul>\n  <li>\n    We will have Kali installed in a VirtualBox machine. One network interface will be in bridge mode with our laptop wireless card.\n    This will produce an Ethernet (wired) connection in the virtual machine. For the second interface, I have a USB wireless internet\n    card (Edimax EW-7811UTC) that I\'ll add to the machine and install there.\n\n    <div class=\"imgs-wrapper\">\n      <img src=\"../../../assets/images/0001.png\" alt=\"Wireless bridged\">\n      <img src=\"../../../assets/images/0002.png\" alt=\"USB wirelees card\">\n    </div>\n    <ul>\n      <li>\n        Remember to add your user to the <code>vboxusers</code> group in order for the USB devices to be shared.<sup><a href=\"#fn1\" id=\"ref1\">[1]</a></sup>\n      </li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n  <br>\n  <li>\n    Install the external wireless card in Kali.\n    <a href=\"https://ubuntuforums.org/showthread.php?t=2228244&p=13042921#post13042921\">This post</a>\n    has excelent guidance on how to do it\n  </li>\n  <br>\n  <li>Verifying interface details. <code>eth0</code> comes from our wireless\n  interface in the laptop. It\'s bridged so it has an IP address on the same network as the host laptop.\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>ifconfig</b>\neth0: flags=4163&lt;UP,BROADCAST,RUNNING,MULTICAST&gt;  mtu 1500\n        inet 192.168.43.163  netmask 255.255.255.0  broadcast 192.168.43.255\n        inet6 fe80::a00:27ff:fe44:ca8f  prefixlen 64  scopeid 0x20&lt;link&gt;\n        ether 08:00:27:44:ca:8f  txqueuelen 1000  (Ethernet)\n        RX packets 35  bytes 3186 (3.1 KiB)\n        RX errors 0  dropped 0  overruns 0  frame 0\n        TX packets 41  bytes 3439 (3.3 KiB)\n        TX errors 0  dropped 0 overruns 0  carrier 0  collisions 0\n\nlo: flags=73&lt;UP,LOOPBACK,RUNNING&gt;  mtu 65536\n        inet 127.0.0.1  netmask 255.0.0.0\n        inet6 ::1  prefixlen 128  scopeid 0x10&lt;host&gt;\n        loop  txqueuelen 1000  (Local Loopback)\n        RX packets 100  bytes 7596 (7.4 KiB)\n        RX errors 0  dropped 0  overruns 0  frame 0\n        TX packets 100  bytes 7596 (7.4 KiB)\n        TX errors 0  dropped 0 overruns 0  carrier 0  collisions 0\n\nwlan0: flags=4099&lt;UP,BROADCAST,MULTICAST&gt;  mtu 1500\n        ether 74:da:38:c9:9a:94  txqueuelen 1000  (Ethernet)\n        RX packets 0  bytes 0 (0.0 B)\n        RX errors 0  dropped 19  overruns 0  frame 0\n        TX packets 0  bytes 0 (0.0 B)\n        TX errors 0  dropped 0 overruns 0  carrier 0  collisions 0\n</pre>\n  </li>\n  <br>\n  <li>Wireless information. <code>iwconfig</code> shows our external wireless card, which for the moment\n    is not connected to any network.\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>iwconfig</b>\nwlan0     unassociated  Nickname:&quot;&lt;WIFI@REALTEK&gt;&quot;\n          Mode:Managed  Frequency=2.412 GHz  Access Point: Not-Associated\n          Sensitivity:0/0\n          Retry:off   RTS thr:off   Fragment thr:off\n          Encryption key:off\n          Power Management:off\n          Link Quality:0  Signal level:0  Noise level:0\n          Rx invalid nwid:0  Rx invalid crypt:0  Rx invalid frag:0\n          Tx excessive retries:0  Invalid misc:0   Missed beacon:0\n\nlo        no wireless extensions.\n\neth0      no wireless extensions.\n</pre>\n    <ul>\n        <li>\n          <code>Tx-Power</code> is the transmit power. In the US is limited to 27 dBm.\n        </li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n  <br>\n  <li>Setup support for ssh\n    <ul>\n      <li>Newer versions of Kali come with a pair public and private keys. If we want to change them, follow <a href =\"http://blog.7-a.org/2013/04/kali-linux-dude-wheres-my-sshd-generate.html\">\n      this blog post</a>.</li>\n      <li>Start the SSH service.\n      </li>\n    </ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>/etc/init.d/ssh start</b>\n[<font color=\"#4E9A06\"> ok </font>] Starting ssh (via systemctl): ssh.service.\n</pre>\n  </li>\n  <br>\n  <li> If we want to configure a static IP address, with the command <code style=\"inline\">ifconfig</code>:\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>ifconfig eth0 down</b>\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>ifconfig eth0 192.168.43.77/24 up</b>\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>route add default gw 192.168.43.1</b>\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>ping 8.8.8.8</b>\nPING 8.8.8.8 (8.8.8.8) 56(84) bytes of data.\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=54 time=704 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=2 ttl=54 time=314 ms\n^C\n--- 8.8.8.8 ping statistics ---\n2 packets transmitted, 2 received, 0% packet loss, time 1001ms\nrtt min/avg/max/mdev = 314.192/509.300/704.409/195.109 ms\n</pre>\n    <ul>\n      <li>We need to configure a DNS server as well.</li>\n    </ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>cat /etc/resolv.conf</b>\n# Generated by NetworkManager\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>ping google.es</b>\nping: google.es: Name or service not known\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>echo nameserver 8.8.8.8 &gt; /etc/resolv.conf</b>\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>ping google.es</b>\nPING google.es (216.58.204.3) 56(84) bytes of data.\n^C64 bytes from 216.58.204.3: icmp_seq=1 ttl=51 time=318 ms\n\n--- google.es ping statistics ---\n1 packets transmitted, 1 received, 0% packet loss, time 0ms\nrtt min/avg/max/mdev = 318.659/318.659/318.659/0.000 ms\n</pre>\n  </li>\n  <br>\n  <li>\n    If we want the changes to stay after rebooting we have to edit the file <code>/etc/network/interfaces</code> instead:\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>cat /etc/network/interfaces</b>\n# This file describes the network interfaces available on your system\n# and how to activate them. For more information, see interfaces(5).\n\nsource /etc/network/interfaces.d/*\n\n# The loopback network interface\nauto lo\niface lo inet loopback\n\n# Wired interface\nauto eth0\niface eth inet static\n  address 192.168.43.222\n  netmask 255.255.255.0\n  network 192.168.43.0\n  broadcast 192.168.43.255\n  gateway 192.168.43.1\n</pre>\n  </li>\n  <br>\n  <li>\n    If we want to keep our SSH settings after reboot (there is a similar command for the network settings but\n    its use is not recommended)\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>update-rc.d -f ssh defaults</b>\n</pre>\n  </li>\n  <br>\n  <li>\n    Configuring the wireless transmission Power\n    <ul>\n      <li>We can alter or manipulate the signal strength on the adapter in the Kali machine</li>\n      <li>\n        Depending on the country that you live in, there\'s very likely a regulatory agency that\'s controlling the airways\n        <sup><a href=\"#fn2\" id=\"ref2\">[2]</a></sup>\n      </li>\n      <li>In one terminal, we use the <code>tail</code> command to see in real time the changes to the log messages file:</li>\n    </ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>tail -f -n 0 /var/log/messages</b>\n</pre>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Instructions to change country code and transmission power:</li>\n    </ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>ifconfig wlan0 down</b>\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>iw reg set US</b>\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>iw reg get</b>\nglobal\ncountry US: DFS-FCC\n	(2402 - 2472 @ 40), (N/A, 30), (N/A)\n	(5170 - 5250 @ 80), (N/A, 23), (N/A), AUTO-BW\n	(5250 - 5330 @ 80), (N/A, 23), (0 ms), DFS, AUTO-BW\n	(5490 - 5730 @ 160), (N/A, 23), (0 ms), DFS\n	(5735 - 5835 @ 80), (N/A, 30), (N/A)\n	(57240 - 63720 @ 2160), (N/A, 40), (N/A)\n\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>iwconfig wlan0 channel 13</b>\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>iwconfig wlan0 txpower 23</b>\nError for wireless request &quot;Set Tx Power&quot; (8B26) :\n    SET failed on device wlan0 ; Operation not permitted.\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>ifconfig wlan0 up</b>\n</pre>\n    <ul>\n      <li>In this wireless card it doesn\'t work. Maybe because of the drivers.</li>\n      <li>System log messages doesn\'t show anything other than the interface up/down messages.</li>\n      <li>Setting the country code to BO or some other place allows for higher transmission power limits.</li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<br>\n<hr>\n<ul>\n  <li>\n    Remainder: useful commands\n    <table>\n      <thead>\n        <tr>\n          <th>Command</th>\n          <th>Description</th>\n        </tr>\n      </thead>\n      <tbody>\n        <tr>\n          <td>\n            <code class=\"inline\">/etc/init.d/networking start</code><br>\n            <code>service networking start</code><br>\n            <code>start networking</code>\n          </td>\n          <td>Enable / disable / restart networking service</td>\n        </tr>\n        <tr>\n          <td>\n            <code class=\"inline\">/etc/init.d/ssh start</code><br>\n          </td>\n          <td>Enable / disable / restart SSH service</td>\n        </tr>\n      </tbody>\n    </table>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<br>\n<hr>\n<sup id=\"fn1\">[1] <a href=\"https://askubuntu.com/questions/282018/wifi-card-on-an-virtualboxs-ubuntu\">https://askubuntu.com/questions/282018/wifi-card-on-an-virtualboxs-ubuntu</a> &nbsp; <a href=\"#ref1\" title=\"Jump back to footnote 1 in the text.\"></a></sup><br>\n<sup id=\"fn2\">[2] <a href=\"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/wireless/wcs/3-2/configuration/guide/wcscfg32/wcscod.pdf\">https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/wireless/wcs/3-2/configuration/guide/wcscfg32/wcscod.pdf</a> [PDF] &nbsp; <a href=\"#ref2\" title=\"Jump back to footnote 2 in the text.\"></a></sup>\n', '2018-01-15 08:38:31'),
(8, 'Absolute minimum configuration for GNS3 devices', 1, '<style>\n</style>\n<h4 class=\"subtitle\">For routers</h4>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">\nhostname R1\nno ip domain lookup\nline con 0\n exec-timeout 0 0\n logging synchronous\n exit\n!For interfaces connected to switches:\nint f0/0\n speed 100\n duplex full\ndo copy run start\n</pre>\n<br>\n<h4 class=\"subtitle\">For switches</h4>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">\nhostname SW1\nno ip routing\nno ip domain lookup\nline con 0\n exec-timeout 0 0\n logging synchronous\n exit\n!For interfaces present on the EhterSwitch module that are\n! connected to other switches, routers or computers:\nint f1/0\n speed 100\n duplex full\ndo copy run start\n</pre>\n<br>\n<h4 class=\"subtitle\">For computers</h4>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">\nhostname PC-A\nno ip routing\nno ip domain lookup\n!For interfaces that are connected to switches\ninterface FastEthernet0/0\n speed 100\n duplex full\nline con 0\n exec-timeout 0 0\n logging synchronous\ndo copy run start\n</pre>\n', '2018-01-20 16:54:06'),
(9, 'CBT Nuggets OSPF Lab', 6, '<style>\n</style>\n<h4 class=\"subtitle\">Setup</h4>\n<img src=\"../../../assets/images/0003.png\" alt=\"Setup\">\n<br>\n<br>\n<h4 class=\"subtitle\">Objectives</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>\n    Configure all routers shown to operate in the backbone area.\n    Hardcode Router IDs so they do not easily change.\n  </li>\n  <li>\n    Determine which router became the DR;\n    elect \"Tie\" as the DR moving forward.\n  </li>\n  <li>\n    Adjust the metric of OSPF to function well with speeds\n    up to 10G links.\n  </li>\n  <li>\n    Ensure \"Shoe\" does not form OSPF neighbors on its LAN network.\n  </li>\n  <li>\n    Adjust the Hello timer on the \"Sock\" WAN interface to send\n    Hello messages 1/sec.\n  </li>\n  <li>\n    <b>Bonus:</b> create loopback interfaces in such a way that\n    Router IDs are pingable from any router.\n  </li>\n</ol>\n<br>\n<h4><b>[1]</b> Base configuration</h4>\n<hr>\n<ul><li>\n  Configure <b>Shoe</b> router.\n</li></ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Shoe(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\nShoe(config-router)# <b>router-id 4.4.4.4</b>\nShoe(config-router)# <b>network 10.1.3.1 0.0.0.0 area 0</b>\nShoe(config-router)# <b>network 10.1.2.2 0.0.0.0 area 0</b>\n</pre>\n<br>\n<ul><li>\n  Configure <b>Sock</b> router. When we add the link that was connected to <b>Shoe</b>,\n  a new neighbor message appears.\n</li></ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Sock(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\nSock(config-router)# <b>router-id 3.3.3.3</b>\nSock(config-router)# <b>network 10.1.2.1 0.0.0.0 area 0</b>\nSock(config-router)#\n*Mar  1 01:08:23.687: %OSPF-5-ADJCHG: Process 1, Nbr 4.4.4.4 on Serial1/0 from LOADING to FULL, Loading Done\nSock(config-router)# <b>network 10.1.1.0 0.0.0.255 area 0</b>\n</pre>\n<br>\n<ul><li>\n  Verification on <b>Sock</b>. We can see 4.4.4.4 as Information Source in <b>show ip protocols</b>.\n  We see that we are in a Full state with <b>Shoe</b>. After <b>FULL</b> we should see if the Device\n  is DR or BDR, but as this connection is PPP, we don\'t.\n</li></ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Sock# <b>show ip protocols</b>\nRouting Protocol is \"ospf 1\"\n  Outgoing update filter list for all interfaces is not set\n  Incoming update filter list for all interfaces is not set\n  Router ID 3.3.3.3\n  Number of areas in this router is 1. 1 normal 0 stub 0 nssa\n  Maximum path: 4\n  Routing for Networks:\n    10.1.1.0 0.0.0.255 area 0\n    10.1.2.1 0.0.0.0 area 0\n Reference bandwidth unit is 100 mbps\n  Routing Information Sources:\n    Gateway         Distance      Last Update\n    3.3.3.3              110      00:02:04\n    4.4.4.4              110      00:02:27\n  Distance: (default is 110)\n\nSock# <b>show ip ospf neighbor</b>\nNeighbor ID     Pri   State           Dead Time   Address         Interface\n4.4.4.4           0   FULL/  -        00:00:33    10.1.2.2        Serial1/0\n\nSock# <b>show ip route</b>\nCodes: C - connected, S - static, R - RIP, M - mobile, B - BGP\n       D - EIGRP, EX - EIGRP external, O - OSPF, IA - OSPF inter area\n       N1 - OSPF NSSA external type 1, N2 - OSPF NSSA external type 2\n       E1 - OSPF external type 1, E2 - OSPF external type 2\n       i - IS-IS, su - IS-IS summary, L1 - IS-IS level-1, L2 - IS-IS level-2\n       ia - IS-IS inter area, * - candidate default, U - per-user static route\n       o - ODR, P - periodic downloaded static route\n\nGateway of last resort is not set\n\n     10.0.0.0/24 is subnetted, 3 subnets\nO       10.1.3.0 [110/65] via 10.1.2.2, 00:16:00, Serial1/0\nC       10.1.2.0 is directly connected, Serial1/0\nC       10.1.1.0 is directly connected, FastEthernet0/0\n</pre>\n<br>\n<ul><li>\n  Configure router <b>Tie</b>. Note that we leave its router ID to be configured automatically.\n</li></ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Tie(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\nTie(config-router)# <b>network 10.1.1.1 0.0.0.0 area 0</b>\nTie(config-router)#\n*Mar  1 01:29:25.775: %OSPF-5-ADJCHG: Process 1, Nbr 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0 from LOADING to FULL, Loading Done\n</pre>\n<br>\n<ul><li>\n  Now, <b>Sock</b> has been automatically configured as a DR and <b>Tie</b> as a BDR.\n</li></ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Sock# <b>show ip ospf neighbor</b>\nNeighbor ID     Pri   State           Dead Time   Address         Interface\n10.1.1.1          1   FULL/BDR        00:00:31    10.1.1.1        FastEthernet0/0\n4.4.4.4           0   FULL/  -        00:00:30    10.1.2.2        Serial1/0\n\nTie# <b>show ip ospf neighbor</b>\nNeighbor ID     Pri   State           Dead Time   Address         Interface\n3.3.3.3           1   FULL/DR         00:00:31    10.1.1.3        FastEthernet0/0\n</pre>\n<br>\n<ul><li>\n  Note that in order to fix a router id missconfiguration, we have to either reboot the router\n  or issue the <b>clear ip ospf process</b> command.\n</li></ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Tie(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\nTie(config-router)# <b>router-id 1.1.1.1</b>\nReload or use \"clear ip ospf process\" command, for this to take effect\nTie(config-router)#^Z\nTie# <b>clear ip ospf process</b>\nReset ALL OSPF processes? [no]: y\nTie#\n*Mar  1 01:35:17.275: %OSPF-5-ADJCHG: Process 1, Nbr 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0 from FULL to DOWN, Neighbor Down: Interface down or detached\n</pre>\n<ul><ul><li>After this, <b>Tie</b> will be the DR for the 10.1.1.0/24 network.</li></ul></ul>\n<br>\n<ul><li>\n  Finish with <b>Belt</b> configuration. We issue the <b>debug</b> command so we can see the process.\n  We see two neighbors forming at the same time\n</li></ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Belt# <b>debug ip ospf adj</b>\nOSPF adjacency events debugging is on\nBelt(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\nBelt(config-router)# <b>router-id 2.2.2.2</b>\nBelt(config-router)# <b>network 10.1.1.2 0.0.0.0 area 0</b>\n\n*Mar  1 01:42:54.503: OSPF: Interface FastEthernet0/0 going Up\n*Mar  1 01:42:54.519: OSPF: 2 Way Communication to 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0, state 2WAY\n*Mar  1 01:42:54.539: OSPF: Rcv DBD from 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0 seq 0x183E opt 0x52 flag 0x7 len 32  mtu 1500 state 2WAY\n*Mar  1 01:42:54.539: OSPF: Nbr state is 2WAY\n*Mar  1 01:42:55.003: OSPF: Build router LSA for area 0, router ID 2.2.2.2, seq 0x80000001, process 1\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.543: OSPF: Rcv DBD from 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0 seq 0x183E opt 0x52 flag 0x7 len 32  mtu 1500 state 2WAY\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.543: OSPF: Nbr state is 2WAY\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.787: OSPF: 2 Way Communication to 1.1.1.1 on FastEthernet0/0, state 2WAY\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.787: OSPF: Backup seen Event before WAIT timer on FastEthernet0/0\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.791: OSPF: DR/BDR election on FastEthernet0/0\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.795: OSPF: Elect BDR 1.1.1.1\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.795: OSPF: Elect DR 3.3.3.3\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.799:        DR: 3.3.3.3 (Id)   BDR: 1.1.1.1 (Id)\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.799: OSPF: Send DBD to 1.1.1.1 on FastEthernet0/0 seq 0x18BA opt 0x52 flag 0x7 len 32\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.803: OSPF: Send DBD to 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0 seq 0x22 opt 0x52 flag 0x7 len 32\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.831: OSPF: Rcv DBD from 1.1.1.1 on FastEthernet0/0 seq 0x2542 opt 0x52 flag 0x7 len 32  mtu 1500 state EXSTART\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.831: OSPF: First DBD and we are not SLAVE\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.839: OSPF: Rcv DBD from 1.1.1.1 on FastEthernet0/0 seq 0x18BA opt 0x52 flag 0x2 len 112  mtu 1500 state EXSTART\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.839: OSPF: NBR Negotiation Done. We are the MASTER\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.843: OSPF: Send DBD to 1.1.1.1 on FastEthernet0/0 seq 0x18BB opt 0x52 flag 0x3 len 52\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.859: OSPF: Rcv DBD from 1.1.1.1 on FastEthernet0/0 seq 0x18BB opt 0x52 flag 0x0 len 32  mtu 1500 state EXCHANGE\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.859: OSPF: Send DBD to 1.1.1.1 on FastEthernet0/0 seq 0x18BC opt 0x52 flag 0x1 len 32\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.863: OSPF: Send LS REQ to 1.1.1.1 length 48 LSA count 4\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.879: OSPF: Rcv LS REQ from 1.1.1.1 on FastEthernet0/0 length 36 LSA count 1\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.883: OSPF: Send UPD to 10.1.1.1 on FastEthernet0/0 length 40 LSA count 1\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.891: OSPF: Rcv DBD from 1.1.1.1 on FastEthernet0/0 seq 0x18BC opt 0x52 flag 0x0 len 32  mtu 1500 state EXCHANGE\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.891: OSPF: Exchange Done with 1.1.1.1 on FastEthernet0/0\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.903: OSPF: Rcv LS UPD from 1.1.1.1 on FastEthernet0/0 length 216 LSA count 4\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.903: OSPF: Synchronized with 1.1.1.1 on FastEthernet0/0, state FULL\n*Mar  1 01:42:59.903: %OSPF-5-ADJCHG: Process 1, Nbr 1.1.1.1 on FastEthernet0/0 from LOADING to FULL, Loading Done\n*Mar  1 01:43:04.543: OSPF: Rcv DBD from 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0 seq 0x183E opt 0x52 flag 0x7 len 32  mtu 1500 state EXSTART\n*Mar  1 01:43:04.547: OSPF: NBR Negotiation Done. We are the SLAVE\n*Mar  1 01:43:04.547: OSPF: Send DBD to 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0 seq 0x183E opt 0x52 flag 0x2 len 132\n*Mar  1 01:43:04.567: OSPF: Rcv DBD from 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0 seq 0x183F opt 0x52 flag 0x3 len 112  mtu 1500 state EXCHANGE\n*Mar  1 01:43:04.567: OSPF: Send DBD to 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0 seq 0x183F opt 0x52 flag 0x0 len 32\n*Mar  1 01:43:04.579: OSPF: Rcv DBD from 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0 seq 0x1840 opt 0x52 flag 0x1 len 32  mtu 1500 state EXCHANGE\n*Mar  1 01:43:04.579: OSPF: Exchange Done with 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0\n*Mar  1 01:43:04.579: OSPF: Synchronized with 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0, state FULL\n*Mar  1 01:43:04.579: %OSPF-5-ADJCHG: Process 1, Nbr 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0 from LOADING to FULL, Loading Done\n*Mar  1 01:43:04.579: OSPF: Send DBD to 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0 seq 0x1840 opt 0x52 flag 0x0 len 32\n*Mar  1 01:43:04.587: OSPF: Rcv LS REQ from 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0 length 36 LSA count 1\n*Mar  1 01:43:04.591: OSPF: Send UPD to 10.1.1.3 on FastEthernet0/0 length 40 LSA count 1\n*Mar  1 01:43:04.599: OSPF: Rcv LS UPD from 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0 length 64 LSA count 1\n*Mar  1 01:43:05.083: OSPF: Build router LSA for area 0, router ID 2.2.2.2, seq 0x80000002, process 1\n*Mar  1 01:43:05.107: OSPF: Rcv LS UPD from 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0 length 64 LSA count 1\n*Mar  1 01:43:05.155: OSPF: Rcv LS UPD from 3.3.3.3 on FastEthernet0/0 length 64 LSA count 1\n</pre>\n<ul><ul>\n  <li>\n    The order is confusing because <b>Tie</b> is communicating with two other routers\n    at the same time. It starts forming 2-WAY relationships with them and after that,\n    negotiations to select the DR and BDR are performed.\n  </li>\n  <li>\n    States: 2-WAY -> EXSTART -> EXCHANGE.\n  </li>\n</ul></ul>\n<br>\n<h4><b>[2]</b> DR election</h4>\n<hr>\n<ul>\n  <li>\n    The automatic choice of the DR may be altered by the order in which we configure\n    the routers or the order in which they reboot, not always setting the one with highest\n    Router ID as a DR. In normal broadcast (Ethernet) networks this is not a big deal.\n  </li>\n  <li>\n    Priority can be manually changed. Remember that if the DR and BDR are already set,\n    nothing will happen until we reset the ospf process on the rest of the routers:\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Tie(config)# <b>int fa0/0</b>\nTie(config-if)# <b>ip ospf priority 10</b>\n</pre>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Belt# <b>clear ip ospf process</b>\nReset ALL OSPF processes? [no]: y\n\nSock# <b>clear ip ospf process</b>\nReset ALL OSPF processes? [no]: y\n</pre>\n<ul>\n  <li>\n    We can verify that Tie was set as the new DR with <b>show ip ospf neighbor</b>\n    or <b>show ip ospf interface</b> commands.\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Sock# <b>sh ip ospf neighbor</b>\nNeighbor ID     Pri   State           Dead Time   Address         Interface\n4.4.4.4           0   FULL/  -        00:00:32    10.1.2.2        Serial1/0\n1.1.1.1          10   FULL/DR         00:00:38    10.1.1.1        FastEthernet0/0\n2.2.2.2           1   FULL/DROTHER    00:00:38    10.1.1.2        FastEthernet0/0\n\nSock# <b>sh ip ospf interface</b>\nSerial1/0 is up, line protocol is up\n  Internet Address 10.1.2.1/24, Area 0\n  Process ID 1, Router ID 3.3.3.3, Network Type POINT_TO_POINT, Cost: 64\n  Transmit Delay is 1 sec, State POINT_TO_POINT\n  Timer intervals configured, Hello 10, Dead 40, Wait 40, Retransmit 5\n    oob-resync timeout 40\n    Hello due in 00:00:05\n  Supports Link-local Signaling (LLS)\n  Cisco NSF helper support enabled\n  IETF NSF helper support enabled\n  Index 2/2, flood queue length 0\n  Next 0x0(0)/0x0(0)\n  Last flood scan length is 1, maximum is 2\n  Last flood scan time is 0 msec, maximum is 4 msec\n  Neighbor Count is 1, Adjacent neighbor count is 1\n    Adjacent with neighbor 4.4.4.4\n  Suppress hello for 0 neighbor(s)\nFastEthernet0/0 is up, line protocol is up\n  Internet Address 10.1.1.3/24, Area 0\n  Process ID 1, Router ID 3.3.3.3, Network Type BROADCAST, Cost: 1\n  Transmit Delay is 1 sec, State BDR, Priority 1\n  Designated Router (ID) 1.1.1.1, Interface address 10.1.1.1\n  Backup Designated router (ID) 3.3.3.3, Interface address 10.1.1.3\n  Timer intervals configured, Hello 10, Dead 40, Wait 40, Retransmit 5\n    oob-resync timeout 40\n    Hello due in 00:00:02\n  Supports Link-local Signaling (LLS)\n  Cisco NSF helper support enabled\n  IETF NSF helper support enabled\n  Index 1/1, flood queue length 0\n  Next 0x0(0)/0x0(0)\n  Last flood scan length is 0, maximum is 1\n  Last flood scan time is 0 msec, maximum is 4 msec\n  Neighbor Count is 2, Adjacent neighbor count is 2\n    Adjacent with neighbor 1.1.1.1  (Designated Router)\n    Adjacent with neighbor 2.2.2.2\n  Suppress hello for 0 neighbor(s)\n\nTie# <b>sh ip ospf int</b>\nFastEthernet0/0 is up, line protocol is up\n  Internet Address 10.1.1.1/24, Area 0\n  Process ID 1, Router ID 1.1.1.1, Network Type BROADCAST, Cost: 1\n  Transmit Delay is 1 sec, State DR, Priority 10\n  Designated Router (ID) 1.1.1.1, Interface address 10.1.1.1\n  Backup Designated router (ID) 3.3.3.3, Interface address 10.1.1.3\n  Timer intervals configured, Hello 10, Dead 40, Wait 40, Retransmit 5\n    oob-resync timeout 40\n    Hello due in 00:00:09\n  Supports Link-local Signaling (LLS)\n  Cisco NSF helper support enabled\n  IETF NSF helper support enabled\n  Index 1/1, flood queue length 0\n  Next 0x0(0)/0x0(0)\n  Last flood scan length is 1, maximum is 1\n  Last flood scan time is 0 msec, maximum is 4 msec\n  Neighbor Count is 2, Adjacent neighbor count is 2\n    Adjacent with neighbor 2.2.2.2\n    Adjacent with neighbor 3.3.3.3  (Backup Designated Router)\n  Suppress hello for 0 neighbor(s)\n</pre>\n<br>\n<ul>\n  <li>\n    In Non-Broadcast Multiaccess Networks (NBMNs), with Hub-And-Spoke topologies,\n    routers \"think\" that they are all directly connected between eachother,\n    but they are not: they get to eachother through the Hub router.\n    In this situation, we want the Hub router to be the DR and the rest (Spoke\n    routers) to never become one. For this purpose, we set their OSPF priority to <b>0</b>.\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<img src=\"../../../assets/images/0004.png\" alt=\"Hub-And-Spoke topology\">\n<br>\n<h4><b>[3]</b> Metric adjustment</h4>\n<hr>\n<ul>\n  <li>\n    OSPF uses a metric known as <b>cost</b>. It is calculated with the formula 100 / (Interface bandwith in Mbps).\n    For example, for T1 (1.544Mbps) it\'s 64 (rounds it). OSPF actually adds up the cost\n    corresponding to all of the interfaces a packet has to go through in order to reach the network.\n    For example, the cost for <b>Sock</b> to reach 10.1.3.0/24 is 65 (the serial link is 64,\n    plus 1 for the FastEthernet interface).\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Sock#sh ip route\nCodes: C - connected, S - static, R - RIP, M - mobile, B - BGP\n       D - EIGRP, EX - EIGRP external, O - OSPF, IA - OSPF inter area\n       N1 - OSPF NSSA external type 1, N2 - OSPF NSSA external type 2\n       E1 - OSPF external type 1, E2 - OSPF external type 2\n       i - IS-IS, su - IS-IS summary, L1 - IS-IS level-1, L2 - IS-IS level-2\n       ia - IS-IS inter area, * - candidate default, U - per-user static route\n       o - ODR, P - periodic downloaded static route\n\nGateway of last resort is not set\n\n     10.0.0.0/24 is subnetted, 3 subnets\nO       10.1.3.0 [110/65] via 10.1.2.2, 00:46:05, Serial1/0\nC       10.1.2.0 is directly connected, Serial1/0\nC       10.1.1.0 is directly connected, FastEthernet0/0\n</pre>\n<br>\n<ul>\n  <li>\n    In order to modify the cost of a link we can change the <b>bandwith</b> value of one interface\n    or hardcode it on the OSPF settings for that interface (not recommended)\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Shoe(config)# <b>int f0/0</b>\nShoe(config-if)# <b>bandwidth 100000</b>\nShoe(config-if)# <b>ip ospf cost 5</b>\n</pre>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Shoe# <b>sh interfaces f0/0</b>\nFastEthernet0/0 is up, line protocol is up\n  Hardware is Gt96k FE, address is c207.0fdb.0000 (bia c207.0fdb.0000)\n  Internet address is 10.1.3.1/24\n  MTU 1500 bytes, BW 100000 Kbit/sec, DLY 100 usec,\n     reliability 255/255, txload 1/255, rxload 1/255\n  Encapsulation ARPA, loopback not set\n  Keepalive set (10 sec)\n  Full-duplex, 100Mb/s, 100BaseTX/FX\n  ARP type: ARPA, ARP Timeout 04:00:00\n  Last input 00:00:55, output 00:00:00, output hang never\n  Last clearing of \"show interface\" counters never\n  Input queue: 0/75/0/0 (size/max/drops/flushes); Total output drops: 0\n  Queueing strategy: fifo\n  Output queue: 0/40 (size/max)\n  5 minute input rate 0 bits/sec, 0 packets/sec\n  5 minute output rate 0 bits/sec, 0 packets/sec\n     106 packets input, 37948 bytes\n     Received 106 broadcasts, 0 runts, 0 giants, 0 throttles\n     0 input errors, 0 CRC, 0 frame, 0 overrun, 0 ignored\n     0 watchdog\n     0 input packets with dribble condition detected\n     1380 packets output, 133221 bytes, 0 underruns\n     0 output errors, 0 collisions, 2 interface resets\n     0 babbles, 0 late collision, 0 deferred\n     0 lost carrier, 0 no carrier\n     0 output buffer failures, 0 output buffers swapped out\n\nShoe# <b>sh ip ospf interface f0/0</b>\nFastEthernet0/0 is up, line protocol is up\n  Internet Address 10.1.3.1/24, Area 0\n  Process ID 1, Router ID 4.4.4.4, Network Type BROADCAST, Cost: 5\n  Transmit Delay is 1 sec, State DR, Priority 1\n  Designated Router (ID) 4.4.4.4, Interface address 10.1.3.1\n  No backup designated router on this network\n  Timer intervals configured, Hello 10, Dead 40, Wait 40, Retransmit 5\n    oob-resync timeout 40\n    Hello due in 00:00:01\n  Supports Link-local Signaling (LLS)\n  Cisco NSF helper support enabled\n  IETF NSF helper support enabled\n  Index 2/2, flood queue length 0\n  Next 0x0(0)/0x0(0)\n  Last flood scan length is 0, maximum is 0\n  Last flood scan time is 0 msec, maximum is 0 msec\n  Neighbor Count is 0, Adjacent neighbor count is 0\n  Suppress hello for 0 neighbor(s)\n</pre>\n<br>\n<ul>\n  <li>\n    This formula is not ready for new technologies, as it rounds everything over\n    100Mbps to cost 1. In order to adapt the formula to modern speeds, we need\n    to change the OSPF settings on each router. This commands allows us to modify\n    the reference bandwith (the number on top of the division in the cost formula)\n    per interface. This reference is given in Mbps.\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Sock(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\nSock(config-router)# <b>auto-cost reference-bandwidth 10000</b>\n% OSPF: Reference bandwidth is changed.\n        Please ensure reference bandwidth is consistent across all routers.\n</pre>\n<br>\n<h4><b>[4]</b> Passive networks</h4>\n<hr>\n<ul>\n  <li>\n    It\'s a good security measure to stop OSPF from sending Hello messages from\n    interfaces in which we don\'t want OSPF (someone can connect another router\n    to the network and fuck things up). Two approaches:\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Shoe(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\nShoe(config-router)# <b>passive-interface fa0/0</b>\n</pre>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Shoe(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\nShoe(config-router)# <b>passive-interface default</b>\nShoe(config-router)# <b>no passive-interface se1/0</b>\n</pre>\n<br>\n<ul>\n  <li>\n    Verification: note the <b>No Hellos (Passive interface)</b> line.\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Shoe# <b>show ip ospf interface f0/0</b>\nFastEthernet0/0 is up, line protocol is up\n  Internet Address 10.1.3.1/24, Area 0\n  Process ID 1, Router ID 4.4.4.4, Network Type BROADCAST, Cost: 5\n  Transmit Delay is 1 sec, State DR, Priority 1\n  Designated Router (ID) 4.4.4.4, Interface address 10.1.3.1\n  No backup designated router on this network\n  Timer intervals configured, Hello 10, Dead 40, Wait 40, Retransmit 5\n    oob-resync timeout 40\n    No Hellos (Passive interface)\n  Supports Link-local Signaling (LLS)\n  Cisco NSF helper support enabled\n  IETF NSF helper support enabled\n  Index 2/2, flood queue length 0\n  Next 0x0(0)/0x0(0)\n  Last flood scan length is 0, maximum is 0\n  Last flood scan time is 0 msec, maximum is 0 msec\n  Neighbor Count is 0, Adjacent neighbor count is 0\n  Suppress hello for 0 neighbor(s)\n</pre>\n<br>\n<h4><b>[5]</b> Hello timer</h4>\n<hr>\n<ul>\n  <li>\n    Hello timer is changed per interface. Remember that we have to change this\n    setting on all other router interfaces connected to that link. Otherwise,\n    the routers won\'t establish neighbor relationships.\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Sock(config-router)# <b>int se1/0</b>\nSock(config-if)# <b>ip ospf hello-interval 1</b>\n</pre>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Shoe(config-router)# <b>int se1/0</b>\nShoe(config-if)# <b>ip ospf hello-interval 1</b>\n</pre>\n<br>\n<ul>\n  <li>\n    Verification:\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Sock# <b>show ip ospf interface se1/0</b>\nSerial1/0 is up, line protocol is up\n  Internet Address 10.1.2.1/24, Area 0\n  Process ID 1, Router ID 3.3.3.3, Network Type POINT_TO_POINT, Cost: 6476\n  Transmit Delay is 1 sec, State POINT_TO_POINT\n  Timer intervals configured, Hello 1, Dead 4, Wait 4, Retransmit 5\n    oob-resync timeout 40\n    Hello due in 00:00:00\n  Supports Link-local Signaling (LLS)\n  Cisco NSF helper support enabled\n  IETF NSF helper support enabled\n  Index 2/2, flood queue length 0\n  Next 0x0(0)/0x0(0)\n  Last flood scan length is 1, maximum is 2\n  Last flood scan time is 0 msec, maximum is 4 msec\n  Neighbor Count is 1, Adjacent neighbor count is 1\n    Adjacent with neighbor 4.4.4.4\n  Suppress hello for 0 neighbor(s)\n</pre>\n<br>\n<ul>\n  <li>\n    Note that thi also changed the dead timer from 40 sec to 4 (it\'s 4 times the\n    Helo interval). This effectively reduces the routes convergence time from\n    40 sec to 4 sec.\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<br>\n<h4><b>[6]</b> Loopback interfaces</h4>\n<hr>\n<ul>\n  <li>\n    We can check our router id with the <b>show ip ospf</b> command. We need to\n    configure the loopback interface and add it as an OSPF route.\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Shoe# <b>show ip ospf</b>\n Routing Process \"ospf 1\" with ID 4.4.4.4\n Start time: 00:00:06.792, Time elapsed: 04:33:33.564\n Supports only single TOS(TOS0) routes\n Supports opaque LSA\n Supports Link-local Signaling (LLS)\n Supports area transit capability\n Router is not originating router-LSAs with maximum metric\n Initial SPF schedule delay 5000 msecs\n Minimum hold time between two consecutive SPFs 10000 msecs\n Maximum wait time between two consecutive SPFs 10000 msecs\n Incremental-SPF disabled\n Minimum LSA interval 5 secs\n Minimum LSA arrival 1000 msecs\n LSA group pacing timer 240 secs\n Interface flood pacing timer 33 msecs\n Retransmission pacing timer 66 msecs\n Number of external LSA 0. Checksum Sum 0x000000\n Number of opaque AS LSA 0. Checksum Sum 0x000000\n Number of DCbitless external and opaque AS LSA 0\n Number of DoNotAge external and opaque AS LSA 0\n Number of areas in this router is 1. 1 normal 0 stub 0 nssa\n Number of areas transit capable is 0\n External flood list length 0\n IETF NSF helper support enabled\n Cisco NSF helper support enabled\n    Area BACKBONE(0)\n	Number of interfaces in this area is 2\n	Area has no authentication\n	SPF algorithm last executed 00:08:24.624 ago\n	SPF algorithm executed 14 times\n	Area ranges are\n	Number of LSA 5. Checksum Sum 0x01EAC4\n	Number of opaque link LSA 0. Checksum Sum 0x000000\n	Number of DCbitless LSA 0\n	Number of indication LSA 0\n	Number of DoNotAge LSA 0\n	Flood list length 0\n\nShoe# <b>conf t</b>\nShoe(config)# <b>interface loopback 0</b>\nShoe(config-if)# <b>ip address 4.4.4.4 255.255.255.255</b>\nShoe(config-if)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\nShoe(config-router)# <b>network 4.4.4.4 0.0.0.0 area 0</b>\n</pre>\n', '2018-01-20 19:02:18'),
(10, 'List of Cisco show commands', 1, '<style>\na.show-command {\n  margin-bottom: 0;\n  font-size: 1.1rem;\n  text-decoration: none;\n  display: inline-block;\n  /* Copied from bootstrap <code>*/\n  font-family: SFMono-Regular,Menlo,Monaco,Consolas,\"Liberation Mono\",\"Courier New\",monospace;\n  padding: .2rem .4rem;\n  color: #bd4147;\n  background-color: #f8f9fa;\n  border-radius: .25rem;\n}\nli.first-level {\n  font-size: 1.5rem;\n  margin-top: 15px;\n}\nli.first-level h4 {\n  margin: 0;\n}\n</style>\n<!--<img src=\"../../../assets/images/00setup.png\" alt=\"Setup\">-->\n<ul>\n  <li class=\"first-level\">\n    <h4>OSPF</h4>\n    <a href=\"#ospf-show-ip-protocols\" class=\"show-command\"><code># <b>show ip protocols</b></code></a><br>\n    <a href=\"#ospf-show-ip-ospf\" class=\"show-command\"><code># <b>show ip ospf</b></code></a><br>\n    <a href=\"#ospf-show-ip-ospf-interface\" class=\"show-command\"><code># <b>show ip ospf interface [fa0/0]</b></code></a><br>\n    <a href=\"#ospf-show-ip-ospf-neighbor\" class=\"show-command\"><code># <b>show ip ospf neighbor</b></code></a><br>\n    <a href=\"#ospf-show-ip-route\" class=\"show-command\"><code># <b>show ip route</b></code></a><br>\n    <a href=\"#ospf-show-run-section-ospf\" class=\"show-command\"><code># <b>show run | section ospf</b></code></a><br>\n  </li>\n  <li class=\"first-level\">\n    <h4>STP</h4>\n    <a href=\"#stp-show-cdp-neighbor\" class=\"show-command\"><code># <b>show cdp neighbor</b></code></a><br>\n    <a href=\"#stp-show-spanning-tree\" class=\"show-command\"><code># <b>show spanning-tree</b></code></a><br>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<br><br>\n<h4>Examples</h4>\n<hr>\n<ul>\n  <li class=\"first-level\">\n    <h4>OSPF</h4>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<pre id=\"ospf-show-ip-protocols\" class=\"terminal\">Sock# <b>show ip protocols</b>\nRouting Protocol is \"ospf 1\"\n  Outgoing update filter list for all interfaces is not set\n  Incoming update filter list for all interfaces is not set\n  Router ID 3.3.3.3\n  Number of areas in this router is 1. 1 normal 0 stub 0 nssa\n  Maximum path: 4\n  Routing for Networks:\n    10.1.1.0 0.0.0.255 area 0\n    10.1.2.1 0.0.0.0 area 0\n Reference bandwidth unit is 100 mbps\n  Routing Information Sources:\n    Gateway         Distance      Last Update\n    3.3.3.3              110      00:02:04\n    4.4.4.4              110      00:02:27\n  Distance: (default is 110)\n</pre>\n<pre id=\"ospf-show-ip-ospf\" class=\"terminal\">Shoe# <b>show ip ospf</b>\n Routing Process \"ospf 1\" with ID 4.4.4.4\n Start time: 00:00:06.792, Time elapsed: 04:33:33.564\n Supports only single TOS(TOS0) routes\n Supports opaque LSA\n Supports Link-local Signaling (LLS)\n Supports area transit capability\n Router is not originating router-LSAs with maximum metric\n Initial SPF schedule delay 5000 msecs\n Minimum hold time between two consecutive SPFs 10000 msecs\n Maximum wait time between two consecutive SPFs 10000 msecs\n Incremental-SPF disabledSock# show ip ospf interface se1/0\nSerial1/0 is up, line protocol is up\n  Internet Address 10.1.2.1/24, Area 0\n  Process ID 1, Router ID 3.3.3.3, Network Type POINT_TO_POINT, Cost: 6476\n  Transmit Delay is 1 sec, State POINT_TO_POINT\n  Timer intervals configured, Hello 1, Dead 4, Wait 4, Retransmit 5\n    oob-resync timeout 40\n    Hello due in 00:00:00\n  Supports Link-local Signaling (LLS)\n  Cisco NSF helper support enabled\n  IETF NSF helper support enabled\n  Index 2/2, flood queue length 0\n  Next 0x0(0)/0x0(0)\n  Last flood scan length is 1, maximum is 2\n  Last flood scan time is 0 msec, maximum is 4 msec\n  Neighbor Count is 1, Adjacent neighbor count is 1\n    Adjacent with neighbor 4.4.4.4\n  Suppress hello for 0 neighbor(s)\n Minimum LSA interval 5 secs\n Minimum LSA arrival 1000 msecs\n LSA group pacing timer 240 secs\n Interface flood pacing timer 33 msecs\n Retransmission pacing timer 66 msecs\n Number of external LSA 0. Checksum Sum 0x000000\n Number of opaque AS LSA 0. Checksum Sum 0x000000\n Number of DCbitless external and opaque AS LSA 0\n Number of DoNotAge external and opaque AS LSA 0\n Number of areas in this router is 1. 1 normal 0 stub 0 nssa\n Number of areas transit capable is 0\n External flood list length 0\n IETF NSF helper support enabled\n Cisco NSF helper support enabled\n    Area BACKBONE(0)\n	Number of interfaces in this area is 2\n	Area has no authentication\n	SPF algorithm last executed 00:08:24.624 ago\n	SPF algorithm executed 14 times\n	Area ranges are\n	Number of LSA 5. Checksum Sum 0x01EAC4\n	Number of opaque link LSA 0. Checksum Sum 0x000000\n	Number of DCbitless LSA 0\n	Number of indication LSA 0\n	Number of DoNotAge LSA 0\n	Flood list length 0\n</pre>\n<pre id=\"ospf-show-ip-ospf-interface\" class=\"terminal\">Shoe# <b>show ip ospf interface f0/0</b>\nFastEthernet0/0 is up, line protocol is up\n  Internet Address 10.1.3.1/24, Area 0\n  Process ID 1, Router ID 4.4.4.4, Network Type BROADCAST, Cost: 5\n  Transmit Delay is 1 sec, State DR, Priority 1\n  Designated Router (ID) 4.4.4.4, Interface address 10.1.3.1\n  No backup designated router on this network\n  Timer intervals configured, Hello 10, Dead 40, Wait 40, Retransmit 5\n    oob-resync timeout 40\n    No Hellos (Passive interface)\n  Supports Link-local Signaling (LLS)\n  Cisco NSF helper support enabled\n  IETF NSF helper support enabled\n  Index 2/2, flood queue length 0\n  Next 0x0(0)/0x0(0)\n  Last flood scan length is 0, maximum is 0\n  Last flood scan time is 0 msec, maximum is 0 msec\n  Neighbor Count is 0, Adjacent neighbor count is 0\n  Suppress hello for 0 neighbor(s)\n\nSock# <b>show ip ospf interface se1/0</b>\nSerial1/0 is up, line protocol is up\n  Internet Address 10.1.2.1/24, Area 0\n  Process ID 1, Router ID 3.3.3.3, Network Type POINT_TO_POINT, Cost: 6476\n  Transmit Delay is 1 sec, State POINT_TO_POINT\n  Timer intervals configured, Hello 1, Dead 4, Wait 4, Retransmit 5\n    oob-resync timeout 40\n    Hello due in 00:00:00\n  Supports Link-local Signaling (LLS)\n  Cisco NSF helper support enabled\n  IETF NSF helper support enabled\n  Index 2/2, flood queue length 0\n  Next 0x0(0)/0x0(0)\n  Last flood scan length is 1, maximum is 2\n  Last flood scan time is 0 msec, maximum is 4 msec\n  Neighbor Count is 1, Adjacent neighbor count is 1\n    Adjacent with neighbor 4.4.4.4\n  Suppress hello for 0 neighbor(s)\n</pre>\n<pre id=\"ospf-show-ip-ospf-neighbor\" class=\"terminal\">Sock# <b>sh ip ospf neighbor</b>\nNeighbor ID     Pri   State           Dead Time   Address         Interface\n4.4.4.4           0   FULL/  -        00:00:32    10.1.2.2        Serial1/0\n1.1.1.1          10   FULL/DR         00:00:38    10.1.1.1        FastEthernet0/0\n2.2.2.2           1   FULL/DROTHER    00:00:38    10.1.1.2        FastEthernet0/0\n</pre>\n<pre id=\"ospf-show-ip-route\" class=\"terminal\">Tie# <b>sh ip route</b>\nCodes: C - connected, S - static, R - RIP, M - mobile, B - BGP\n       D - EIGRP, EX - EIGRP external, O - OSPF, IA - OSPF inter area\n       N1 - OSPF NSSA external type 1, N2 - OSPF NSSA external type 2\n       E1 - OSPF external type 1, E2 - OSPF external type 2\n       i - IS-IS, su - IS-IS summary, L1 - IS-IS level-1, L2 - IS-IS level-2\n       ia - IS-IS inter area, * - candidate default, U - per-user static route\n       o - ODR, P - periodic downloaded static route\n\nGateway of last resort is 10.0.0.2 to network 0.0.0.0\n\n     10.0.0.0/8 is variably subnetted, 10 subnets, 2 masks\nO       10.2.0.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:18:21, Serial1/0\nO       10.2.0.0/21 is a summary, 00:18:21, Null0\nC       10.2.1.0/24 is directly connected, Serial1/0\nO       10.2.2.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:18:21, Serial1/0\nC       10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected, FastEthernet0/0\nO       10.2.3.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:18:21, Serial1/0\nO IA    10.1.0.0/21 [110/65] via 10.0.0.2, 00:18:21, FastEthernet0/0\nO       10.2.4.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:18:22, Serial1/0\nO       10.2.5.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:18:22, Serial1/0\nO IA    10.51.0.0/21 [110/65] via 10.0.0.3, 00:17:44, FastEthernet0/0\nO*E2 0.0.0.0/0 [110/1] via 10.0.0.2, 00:01:34, FastEthernet0/0\n</pre>\n<pre id=\"ospf-show-run-section-ospf\" class=\"terminal\">\n</pre>\n<br>\n<ul>\n  <li class=\"first-level\">\n    <h4>STP</h4>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<pre id=\"stp-show-cdp-neighbor\" class=\"terminal\">S1# <b>show cdp neighbor</b>\nCapability Codes: R - Router, T - Trans Bridge, B - Source Route Bridge\n                  S - Switch, H - Host, I - IGMP, r - Repeater\n\nDevice ID        Local Intrfce     Holdtme    Capability  Platform  Port ID\nS3               Fas 1/3            176          S I      3725      Fas 1/0\nS2               Fas 1/2            152          S I      3725      Fas 1/0\nS5               Fas 1/5            127          S I      3725      Fas 1/0\nS4               Fas 1/4            173          S I      3725      Fas 1/0\n</pre>\n<pre id=\"stp-show-spanning-tree\" class=\"terminal\">! On a real switch we would see port role as well (Root/Desg/Altn)\nS1# <b>show spanning-tree</b>\nVLAN1\n  Spanning tree enabled protocol ieee\n  Root ID    Priority    32768\n             Address     c205.0971.0000\n             Cost        19\n             Port        46 (FastEthernet1/5)\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\n\n  Bridge ID  Priority    32768\n             Address     c207.0961.0000\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\n             Aging Time 300\n\nInterface                                   Designated\nName                 Port ID Prio Cost  Sts Cost  Bridge ID            Port ID\n-------------------- ------- ---- ----- --- ----- -------------------- -------\nFastEthernet1/2      128.43   128    19 BLK    19 32768 c206.0961.0000 128.41\nFastEthernet1/3      128.44   128    19 FWD    19 32768 c207.0961.0000 128.44\nFastEthernet1/4      128.45   128    19 FWD    19 32768 c207.0961.0000 128.45\nFastEthernet1/5      128.46   128    19 FWD     0 32768 c205.0971.0000 128.41\n\n\nS5# <b>show spanning-tree</b>\nVLAN1\n  Spanning tree enabled protocol ieee\n  Root ID    Priority    32768\n             Address     c205.0971.0000\n             This bridge is the root\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\n\n  Bridge ID  Priority    32768\n             Address     c205.0971.0000\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\n             Aging Time 300\n\nInterface                                   Designated\nName                 Port ID Prio Cost  Sts Cost  Bridge ID            Port ID\n-------------------- ------- ---- ----- --- ----- -------------------- -------\nFastEthernet1/0      128.41   128    19 FWD     0 32768 c205.0971.0000 128.41\nFastEthernet1/1      128.42   128    19 FWD     0 32768 c205.0971.0000 128.42\n</pre>\n<br>\n', '2018-01-21 17:09:20'),
(11, 'CBT Nuggets OSPF Multiarea Lab', 6, '<style>\r\n</style>\r\n<h4 class=\"subtitle\">Setup</h4>\r\n<img src=\"../../../assets/images/0005.png\" alt=\"Setup\">\r\n<br>\r\n<br>\r\n<h4 class=\"subtitle\">Objectives</h4>\r\n<ol>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Configure all routers shown to operate in a multiarea configuration.\r\n    Tie, belt, and Sock will act as ABRs.\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Add five (5) loopback interfaces to Ring, Hat and Shoe.\r\n    They should be contiguous to existing area subnets.\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Add an efficient summary route for area 1, 2 and 51. Verify impact\r\n    on the routing table of other routers.\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Add a loopback interface to Belt with the IP address 184.51.1.2/24\r\n    and a default route to 184.51.1.1. This will simulate an Internet\r\n    connection.\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Have Belt advertise the default route to the other routes via OSPF.\r\n    The route should exist even if Belt does not have a default route.\r\n  </li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<br>\r\n<h4><b>[1, 2]</b> Multiarea configuration and loopback interfaces</h4>\r\n<hr>\r\n<ul><li>\r\n  Blow away all previous OSPF configuration and change IP addresses.\r\n</li></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Belt(config)# <b>no router ospf 1</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<ul><li>\r\n  Configure OSPF. You create an Area Border Router (ABR) by assigning\r\n  different interfaces to different areas. We also will configure the\r\n  loopback interfaces as requested.\r\n</li></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Belt(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\r\nBelt(config-router)# <b>network 10.0.0.2 0.0.0.0 area 0</b>\r\nBelt(config-router)# <b>network 10.1.1.1 0.0.0.0 area 1</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Ring(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\r\nRing(config-router)# <b>network 10.1.1.2 0.0.0.0 area 1</b>\r\nRing(config)# <b>interface loopback 0</b>\r\nRing(config-if)# <b>ip address 10.1.0.1 255.255.255.0</b>\r\nRing(config-if)# <b>ip ospf network point-to-point</b>\r\nRing(config-if)# <b>interface loopback 1</b>\r\nRing(config-if)# <b>ip address 10.1.2.1 255.255.255.0</b>\r\nRing(config-if)# <b>ip ospf network point-to-point</b>\r\nRing(config-if)# <b>interface loopback 2</b>\r\nRing(config-if)# <b>ip address 10.1.3.1 255.255.255.0</b>\r\nRing(config-if)# <b>ip ospf network point-to-point</b>\r\nRing(config-if)# <b>interface loopback 3</b>\r\nRing(config-if)# <b>ip address 10.1.4.1 255.255.255.0</b>\r\nRing(config-if)# <b>ip ospf network point-to-point</b>\r\nRing(config-if)# <b>interface loopback 4</b>\r\nRing(config-if)# <b>ip address 10.1.5.1 255.255.255.0</b>\r\nRing(config-if)# <b>ip ospf network point-to-point</b>\r\nRing(config-if)# <b>exit</b>\r\nRing(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\r\nRing(config-router)# <b>network 10.1.0.0 0.0.255.255 area 1</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<ul><ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Notice that here we \"get lazy\" and don\'t write the <b>network</b>\r\n    command interface by interface, as per Cisco recommendations.\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    We need the command <b>ip ospf network point-to-point</b>\r\n    because OSPF recognises the interface as a loopback, and will\r\n    advertise it as a host route (/32). We want it to advertise it as a /24 route.\r\n    Let\'s see what happens when we don\'t issue this command (look at the network\r\n    type in <b>show ip ospf interface</b>, and note that it appears in other\r\n    routers as a /32 route). <b>show ip ospf interface</b> even tells us that\r\n    loopback7 is being treated as a stub host:\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Shoe(config)# <b>interface loopback 7</b>\r\nShoe(config-if)# <b>ip address 10.51.7.1 255.255.255.0</b>\r\nShoe(config-if)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\r\nShoe(config-router)# <b>network 10.51.7.1 0.0.0.0 area 51</b>\r\nShoe(config-router)# <b>^Z</b>\r\nShoe# <b>show ip ospf interface lo0</b>\r\nLoopback0 is up, line protocol is up\r\n  Internet Address 10.51.0.1/24, Area 51\r\n  Process ID 1, Router ID 4.4.4.4, Network Type POINT_TO_POINT, Cost: 1\r\n  Transmit Delay is 1 sec, State POINT_TO_POINT\r\n  Timer intervals configured, Hello 10, Dead 40, Wait 40, Retransmit 5\r\n    oob-resync timeout 40\r\n  Supports Link-local Signaling (LLS)\r\n  Cisco NSF helper support enabled\r\n  IETF NSF helper support enabled\r\n  Index 2/2, flood queue length 0\r\n  Next 0x0(0)/0x0(0)\r\n  Last flood scan length is 0, maximum is 0\r\n  Last flood scan time is 0 msec, maximum is 0 msec\r\n  Neighbor Count is 0, Adjacent neighbor count is 0\r\n  Suppress hello for 0 neighbor(s)\r\nShoe# <b>show ip ospf interface lo7</b>\r\nLoopback7 is up, line protocol is up\r\n  Internet Address 10.51.7.1/24, Area 51\r\n  Process ID 1, Router ID 4.4.4.4, Network Type LOOPBACK, Cost: 1\r\n  Loopback interface is treated as a stub Host\r\n</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Belt#sh ip route\r\nCodes: C - connected, S - static, R - RIP, M - mobile, B - BGP\r\n!! Many lines omitted...\r\n\r\n     10.0.0.0/8 is variably subnetted, 20 subnets, 2 masks\r\n!! Many lines omitted...\r\nO IA    10.51.1.0/24 [110/65] via 10.0.0.3, 00:41:48, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.51.0.0/24 [110/66] via 10.0.0.3, 00:32:36, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.51.3.0/24 [110/66] via 10.0.0.3, 00:32:36, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.51.2.0/24 [110/66] via 10.0.0.3, 00:32:36, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.51.5.0/24 [110/66] via 10.0.0.3, 00:32:36, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.51.4.0/24 [110/66] via 10.0.0.3, 00:32:36, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.51.7.1/32 [110/66] via 10.0.0.3, 00:04:26, FastEthernet0/0\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Check the routes.\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Ring# <b>sh ip route</b>\r\nCodes: C - connected, S - static, R - RIP, M - mobile, B - BGP\r\n       D - EIGRP, EX - EIGRP external, O - OSPF, IA - OSPF inter area\r\n       N1 - OSPF NSSA external type 1, N2 - OSPF NSSA external type 2\r\n       E1 - OSPF external type 1, E2 - OSPF external type 2\r\n       i - IS-IS, su - IS-IS summary, L1 - IS-IS level-1, L2 - IS-IS level-2\r\n       ia - IS-IS inter area, * - candidate default, U - per-user static route\r\n       o - ODR, P - periodic downloaded static route\r\n\r\nGateway of last resort is not set\r\n\r\n     10.0.0.0/24 is subnetted, 7 subnets\r\nC       10.1.3.0 is directly connected, Loopback2\r\nC       10.1.2.0 is directly connected, Loopback1\r\nC       10.1.1.0 is directly connected, Serial1/0\r\nO IA    10.0.0.0 [110/65] via 10.1.1.1, 00:23:34, Serial1/0\r\nC       10.1.0.0 is directly connected, Loopback0\r\nC       10.1.5.0 is directly connected, Loopback4\r\nC       10.1.4.0 is directly connected, Loopback3\r\n</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Belt# <b>show ip route</b>\r\nCodes: C - connected, S - static, R - RIP, M - mobile, B - BGP\r\n       D - EIGRP, EX - EIGRP external, O - OSPF, IA - OSPF inter area\r\n       N1 - OSPF NSSA external type 1, N2 - OSPF NSSA external type 2\r\n       E1 - OSPF external type 1, E2 - OSPF external type 2\r\n       i - IS-IS, su - IS-IS summary, L1 - IS-IS level-1, L2 - IS-IS level-2\r\n       ia - IS-IS inter area, * - candidate default, U - per-user static route\r\n       o - ODR, P - periodic downloaded static route\r\n\r\nGateway of last resort is not set\r\n\r\n     10.0.0.0/24 is subnetted, 7 subnets\r\nO       10.1.3.0 [110/65] via 10.1.1.2, 00:06:57, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.1.2.0 [110/65] via 10.1.1.2, 00:06:57, Serial1/0\r\nC       10.1.1.0 is directly connected, Serial1/0\r\nC       10.0.0.0 is directly connected, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO       10.1.0.0 [110/65] via 10.1.1.2, 00:06:57, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.1.5.0 [110/65] via 10.1.1.2, 00:06:57, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.1.4.0 [110/65] via 10.1.1.2, 00:06:57, Serial1/0\r\n</pre>\r\n<ul><ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    <b>Ring</b> sees 10.0.0.0/24 as an <b>IA</b> (InterArea) route because\r\n    the route belongs to Area 0 and the router is on Area 1.\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    <b>Belt</b> is an ABR (\"belongs to Area 0 and 1\"), so he doens\'t see\r\n    these routes as interarea;\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul></ul>\r\n<ul><li> Configure the rest of the things</li></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Tie(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\r\nTie(config-router)# <b>network 10.0.0.1 0.0.0.0 area 0</b>\r\nTie(config-router)# <b>network 10.2.1.1 0.0.0.0 area 2</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Tie(config)# <b>show ip route</b>\r\nCodes: C - connected, S - static, R - RIP, M - mobile, B - BGP\r\n       D - EIGRP, EX - EIGRP external, O - OSPF, IA - OSPF inter area\r\n       N1 - OSPF NSSA external type 1, N2 - OSPF NSSA external type 2\r\n       E1 - OSPF external type 1, E2 - OSPF external type 2\r\n       i - IS-IS, su - IS-IS summary, L1 - IS-IS level-1, L2 - IS-IS level-2\r\n       ia - IS-IS inter area, * - candidate default, U - per-user static route\r\n       o - ODR, P - periodic downloaded static route\r\n\r\nGateway of last resort is not set\r\n\r\n     10.0.0.0/24 is subnetted, 8 subnets\r\nO IA    10.1.3.0 [110/66] via 10.0.0.2, 00:04:47, FastEthernet0/0\r\nC       10.2.1.0 is directly connected, Serial1/0\r\nO IA    10.1.2.0 [110/66] via 10.0.0.2, 00:04:47, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.1.1.0 [110/65] via 10.0.0.2, 00:04:47, FastEthernet0/0\r\nC       10.0.0.0 is directly connected, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.1.0.0 [110/66] via 10.0.0.2, 00:04:47, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.1.5.0 [110/66] via 10.0.0.2, 00:04:47, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.1.4.0 [110/66] via 10.0.0.2, 00:04:48, FastEthernet0/0\r\n</pre>\r\n<ul><ul><li>\r\n  We can see here that, without route summarization, OSPF just advertises all\r\n  the routes. It is the same as if all the routes were in area 0!\r\n</ul></ul></li>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Hat(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\r\nHat(config-router)# <b>network 10.2.1.2 0.0.0.0 area 2</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">\r\nSock(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\r\nSock(config-router)# <b>network 10.0.0.3 0.0.0.0 area 0</b>\r\nSock(config-router)# <b>network 10.51.1.1 0.0.0.0 area 51</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Shoe(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\r\nShoe(config-router)# <b>network 10.51.1.2 0.0.0.0 area 51</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Hat(config)# <b>interface loopback 0</b>\r\nHat(config-if)# <b>ip address 10.2.0.1 255.255.255.0</b>\r\nHat(config-if)# <b>ip ospf network point-to-point</b>\r\nHat(config-if)# <b>interface loopback 1</b>\r\nHat(config-if)# <b>ip address 10.2.2.1 255.255.255.0</b>\r\nHat(config-if)# <b>ip ospf network point-to-point</b>\r\nHat(config-if)# <b>interface loopback 2</b>\r\nHat(config-if)# <b>ip address 10.2.3.1 255.255.255.0</b>\r\nHat(config-if)# <b>ip ospf network point-to-point</b>\r\nHat(config-if)# <b>interface loopback 3</b>\r\nHat(config-if)# <b>ip address 10.2.4.1 255.255.255.0</b>\r\nHat(config-if)# <b>ip ospf network point-to-point</b>\r\nHat(config-if)# <b>interface loopback 4</b>\r\nHat(config-if)# <b>ip address 10.2.5.1 255.255.255.0</b>\r\nHat(config-if)# <b>ip ospf network point-to-point</b>\r\n\r\nHat(config-if)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\r\nHat(config-router)# <b>network 10.2.0.0 0.0.255.255 area 2</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Shoe(config)# <b>interface loopback 0</b>\r\nShoe(config-if)# <b>ip address 10.51.0.1 255.255.255.0</b>\r\nShoe(config-if)# <b>ip ospf network point-to-point</b>\r\nShoe(config-if)# <b>interface loopback 1</b>\r\nShoe(config-if)# <b>ip address 10.51.2.1 255.255.255.0</b>\r\nShoe(config-if)# <b>ip ospf network point-to-point</b>\r\nShoe(config-if)# <b>interface loopback 2</b>\r\nShoe(config-if)# <b>ip address 10.51.3.1 255.255.255.0</b>\r\nShoe(config-if)# <b>ip ospf network point-to-point</b>\r\nShoe(config-if)# <b>interface loopback 3</b>\r\nShoe(config-if)# <b>ip address 10.51.4.1 255.255.255.0</b>\r\nShoe(config-if)# <b>ip ospf network point-to-point</b>\r\nShoe(config-if)# <b>interface loopback 4</b>\r\nShoe(config-if)# <b>ip address 10.51.5.1 255.255.255.0</b>\r\nShoe(config-if)# <b>ip ospf network point-to-point</b>\r\n\r\nShoe(config-if)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\r\nShoe(config-router)# <b>network 10.51.0.0 0.0.255.255 area 51</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    The routing table now, without summarization, is pretty long (all the routers\r\n    know all the different networks).\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Doing multiarea OSPF without summarization has no point.\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Belt# <b>sh ip route</b>\r\nCodes: C - connected, S - static, R - RIP, M - mobile, B - BGP\r\n       D - EIGRP, EX - EIGRP external, O - OSPF, IA - OSPF inter area\r\n       N1 - OSPF NSSA external type 1, N2 - OSPF NSSA external type 2\r\n       E1 - OSPF external type 1, E2 - OSPF external type 2\r\n       i - IS-IS, su - IS-IS summary, L1 - IS-IS level-1, L2 - IS-IS level-2\r\n       ia - IS-IS inter area, * - candidate default, U - per-user static route\r\n       o - ODR, P - periodic downloaded static route\r\n\r\nGateway of last resort is not set\r\n\r\n     10.0.0.0/8 is variably subnetted, 20 subnets, 2 masks\r\nO IA    10.2.0.0/24 [110/66] via 10.0.0.1, 00:39:46, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO       10.1.3.0/24 [110/65] via 10.1.1.2, 01:23:10, Serial1/0\r\nO IA    10.2.1.0/24 [110/65] via 10.0.0.1, 01:00:32, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO       10.1.2.0/24 [110/65] via 10.1.1.2, 01:23:10, Serial1/0\r\nO IA    10.2.2.0/24 [110/66] via 10.0.0.1, 00:39:46, FastEthernet0/0\r\nC       10.1.1.0/24 is directly connected, Serial1/0\r\nC       10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.2.3.0/24 [110/66] via 10.0.0.1, 00:39:47, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO       10.1.0.0/24 [110/65] via 10.1.1.2, 01:23:11, Serial1/0\r\nO IA    10.2.4.0/24 [110/66] via 10.0.0.1, 00:39:47, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.2.5.0/24 [110/66] via 10.0.0.1, 00:39:47, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO       10.1.5.0/24 [110/65] via 10.1.1.2, 01:23:11, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.1.4.0/24 [110/65] via 10.1.1.2, 01:23:12, Serial1/0\r\nO IA    10.51.1.0/24 [110/65] via 10.0.0.3, 00:50:10, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.51.0.0/24 [110/66] via 10.0.0.3, 00:40:59, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.51.3.0/24 [110/66] via 10.0.0.3, 00:40:59, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.51.2.0/24 [110/66] via 10.0.0.3, 00:40:59, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.51.5.0/24 [110/66] via 10.0.0.3, 00:40:59, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.51.4.0/24 [110/66] via 10.0.0.3, 00:40:59, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.51.7.1/32 [110/66] via 10.0.0.3, 00:12:48, FastEthernet0/0\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<h4><b>[3]</b> Summarization</h4>\r\n<hr>\r\n<ul><li>\r\n  Configure summarization with the area command in ospf configuration\r\n</li></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Belt(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\r\nBelt(config-router)# <b>area 1 ?</b>\r\n  authentication  Enable authentication\r\n  default-cost    Set the summary default-cost of a NSSA/stub area\r\n  filter-list     Filter networks between OSPF areas\r\n  nssa            Specify a NSSA area\r\n  range           Summarize routes matching address/mask (border routers only)\r\n  sham-link       Define a sham link and its parameters\r\n  stub            Specify a stub area\r\n  virtual-link    Define a virtual link and its parameters\r\n\r\nBelt(config-router)# <b>area 1 range 10.1.0.0 255.255.0.0</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Tie(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\r\nTie(config-router)# <b>area 2 range 10.2.0.0 255.255.0.0</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<ul><li>Now the routing table is better</li></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Sock# <b>sh ip route</b>\r\nCodes: C - connected, S - static, R - RIP, M - mobile, B - BGP\r\n       D - EIGRP, EX - EIGRP external, O - OSPF, IA - OSPF inter area\r\n       N1 - OSPF NSSA external type 1, N2 - OSPF NSSA external type 2\r\n       E1 - OSPF external type 1, E2 - OSPF external type 2\r\n       i - IS-IS, su - IS-IS summary, L1 - IS-IS level-1, L2 - IS-IS level-2\r\n       ia - IS-IS inter area, * - candidate default, U - per-user static route\r\n       o - ODR, P - periodic downloaded static route\r\n\r\nGateway of last resort is not set\r\n\r\n     10.0.0.0/8 is variably subnetted, 11 subnets, 3 masks\r\nO IA    10.2.0.0/16 [110/65] via 10.0.0.1, 00:00:32, FastEthernet0/0\r\nC       10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.1.0.0/16 [110/65] via 10.0.0.2, 00:00:32, FastEthernet0/0\r\nC       10.51.1.0/24 is directly connected, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.51.0.0/24 [110/65] via 10.51.1.2, 00:00:32, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.51.0.0/16 is a summary, 00:00:32, Null0\r\nO       10.51.3.0/24 [110/65] via 10.51.1.2, 00:00:32, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.51.2.0/24 [110/65] via 10.51.1.2, 00:00:33, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.51.5.0/24 [110/65] via 10.51.1.2, 00:00:33, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.51.4.0/24 [110/65] via 10.51.1.2, 00:00:33, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.51.7.1/32 [110/65] via 10.51.1.2, 00:00:33, Serial1/0\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    This configuration works but it prevents you from using any of the\r\n    10.1.0.0, 10.2.0.0, 10.51.0.0 anywhere on your network outside of\r\n    their respective areas. This is wasteful.\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    We can use a custom subnet mask to be more efficient. We will use the\r\n    most specific subnet mask that includes our networks (/21 in this case)\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Belt(config-router)# <b>no area 1 range 10.1.0.0 255.255.0.0</b>\r\nBelt(config-router)# <b>area 1 range 10.1.0.0 255.255.248.0</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Tie(config-router)# <b>no area 2 range 10.2.0.0 255.255.0.0</b>\r\nTie(config-router)# <b>area 2 range 10.2.0.0 255.255.248.0</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Sock(config-router)# <b>no area 51 range 10.51.0.0 255.255.0.0</b>\r\nSock(config-router)# <b>area 51 range 10.51.0.0 255.255.248.0</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<ul><li>Now we could use the rest of the subnets in other areas</li></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Sock# <b>sh ip route</b>\r\nCodes: C - connected, S - static, R - RIP, M - mobile, B - BGP\r\n       D - EIGRP, EX - EIGRP external, O - OSPF, IA - OSPF inter area\r\n       N1 - OSPF NSSA external type 1, N2 - OSPF NSSA external type 2\r\n       E1 - OSPF external type 1, E2 - OSPF external type 2\r\n       i - IS-IS, su - IS-IS summary, L1 - IS-IS level-1, L2 - IS-IS level-2\r\n       ia - IS-IS inter area, * - candidate default, U - per-user static route\r\n       o - ODR, P - periodic downloaded static route\r\n\r\nGateway of last resort is not set\r\n\r\n     10.0.0.0/8 is variably subnetted, 11 subnets, 3 masks\r\nO IA    10.2.0.0/21 [110/65] via 10.0.0.1, 00:02:36, FastEthernet0/0\r\nC       10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO IA    10.1.0.0/21 [110/65] via 10.0.0.2, 00:02:36, FastEthernet0/0\r\nC       10.51.1.0/24 is directly connected, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.51.0.0/24 [110/65] via 10.51.1.2, 00:02:36, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.51.0.0/21 is a summary, 00:02:36, Null0\r\nO       10.51.3.0/24 [110/65] via 10.51.1.2, 00:02:36, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.51.2.0/24 [110/65] via 10.51.1.2, 00:02:37, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.51.5.0/24 [110/65] via 10.51.1.2, 00:02:37, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.51.4.0/24 [110/65] via 10.51.1.2, 00:02:37, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.51.7.1/32 [110/65] via 10.51.1.2, 00:02:37, Serial1/0\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<h4><b>[4, 5]</b> Default routing</h4>\r\n<hr>\r\n<ul><li>\r\n  Configure the loopback interface, the default route and\r\n  make Belt advertise it.\r\n</li></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Belt(config)# <b>interface lo10</b>\r\nBelt(config-if)# <b>ip address 184.51.1.2 255.255.255.0</b>\r\nBelt(config)# <b>ip route 0.0.0.0 0.0.0.0 184.51.1.1</b>\r\nBelt(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\r\nBelt(config-router)# <b>default-information originate</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<ul><li>\r\n  Verify in other routers\r\n</li></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Tie# <b>sh ip route</b>\r\nCodes: C - connected, S - static, R - RIP, M - mobile, B - BGP\r\n       D - EIGRP, EX - EIGRP external, O - OSPF, IA - OSPF inter area\r\n       N1 - OSPF NSSA external type 1, N2 - OSPF NSSA external type 2\r\n       E1 - OSPF external type 1, E2 - OSPF external type 2\r\n       i - IS-IS, su - IS-IS summary, L1 - IS-IS level-1, L2 - IS-IS level-2\r\n       ia - IS-IS inter area, * - candidate default, U - per-user static route\r\n       o - ODR, P - periodic downloaded static route\r\n\r\nGateway of last resort is 10.0.0.2 to network 0.0.0.0\r\n\r\n     10.0.0.0/8 is variably subnetted, 10 subnets, 2 masks\r\nO       10.2.0.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:18:21, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.2.0.0/21 is a summary, 00:18:21, Null0\r\nC       10.2.1.0/24 is directly connected, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.2.2.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:18:21, Serial1/0\r\nC       10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO       10.2.3.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:18:21, Serial1/0\r\nO IA    10.1.0.0/21 [110/65] via 10.0.0.2, 00:18:21, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO       10.2.4.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:18:22, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.2.5.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:18:22, Serial1/0\r\nO IA    10.51.0.0/21 [110/65] via 10.0.0.3, 00:17:44, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO*E2 0.0.0.0/0 [110/1] via 10.0.0.2, 00:01:34, FastEthernet0/0\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    The router <b>Belt</b> becomes an <b>ASBR</b> (<b>Autonomous\r\n    System Boundary Router</b>).\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    If we <b>shutdown</b> the interface <b>loopback 10</b>, the default\r\n    route will disappear from the routing table. Thus it will stop advertising\r\n    it and the rest of the routers won\'t have the default route.\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Belt(config)# <b>int lo10</b>\r\nBelt(config-if)# <b>shutdown</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Tie# <b>sh ip ro</b>\r\nCodes: C - connected, S - static, R - RIP, M - mobile, B - BGP\r\n       D - EIGRP, EX - EIGRP external, O - OSPF, IA - OSPF inter area\r\n       N1 - OSPF NSSA external type 1, N2 - OSPF NSSA external type 2\r\n       E1 - OSPF external type 1, E2 - OSPF external type 2\r\n       i - IS-IS, su - IS-IS summary, L1 - IS-IS level-1, L2 - IS-IS level-2\r\n       ia - IS-IS inter area, * - candidate default, U - per-user static route\r\n       o - ODR, P - periodic downloaded static route\r\n\r\nGateway of last resort is not set\r\n\r\n     10.0.0.0/8 is variably subnetted, 10 subnets, 2 masks\r\nO       10.2.0.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:05:27, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.2.0.0/21 is a summary, 00:05:37, Null0\r\nC       10.2.1.0/24 is directly connected, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.2.2.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:05:27, Serial1/0\r\nC       10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO       10.2.3.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:05:27, Serial1/0\r\nO IA    10.1.0.0/21 [110/65] via 10.0.0.2, 00:04:55, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO       10.2.4.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:05:28, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.2.5.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:05:28, Serial1/0\r\nO IA    10.51.0.0/21 [110/65] via 10.0.0.3, 00:05:07, FastEthernet0/0\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<ul><li>\r\n  To advertise the route in any case (even if we don\'t have one or it is down),\r\n  we use <b>always</b>.\r\n</li></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Belt(config)# <b>router ospf 1</b>\r\nBelt(config-router)# <b>default-information originate ?</b>\r\n  always       Always advertise default route\r\n  metric       OSPF default metric\r\n  metric-type  OSPF metric type for default routes\r\n  route-map    Route-map reference\r\n\r\nBelt(config-router)# <b>default-information originate always</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<ul><li>Check the routing tables now:</li></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">Tie# <b>sh ip ro</b>\r\nCodes: C - connected, S - static, R - RIP, M - mobile, B - BGP\r\n       D - EIGRP, EX - EIGRP external, O - OSPF, IA - OSPF inter area\r\n       N1 - OSPF NSSA external type 1, N2 - OSPF NSSA external type 2\r\n       E1 - OSPF external type 1, E2 - OSPF external type 2\r\n       i - IS-IS, su - IS-IS summary, L1 - IS-IS level-1, L2 - IS-IS level-2\r\n       ia - IS-IS inter area, * - candidate default, U - per-user static route\r\n       o - ODR, P - periodic downloaded static route\r\n\r\nGateway of last resort is 10.0.0.2 to network 0.0.0.0\r\n\r\n     10.0.0.0/8 is variably subnetted, 10 subnets, 2 masks\r\nO       10.2.0.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:09:28, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.2.0.0/21 is a summary, 00:09:38, Null0\r\nC       10.2.1.0/24 is directly connected, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.2.2.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:09:28, Serial1/0\r\nC       10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO       10.2.3.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:09:28, Serial1/0\r\nO IA    10.1.0.0/21 [110/65] via 10.0.0.2, 00:08:56, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO       10.2.4.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:09:29, Serial1/0\r\nO       10.2.5.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:09:29, Serial1/0\r\nO IA    10.51.0.0/21 [110/65] via 10.0.0.3, 00:09:07, FastEthernet0/0\r\nO*E2 0.0.0.0/0 [110/1] via 10.0.0.2, 00:01:57, FastEthernet0/0\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n', '2018-01-25 09:47:28'),
(12, 'CBT Nuggets STP Lab', 6, '<style>\r\nimg {\r\n  display:block;\r\n  margin: 0 auto 5px auto;\r\n}\r\n</style>\r\n<h4 class=\"subtitle\">Setup</h4>\r\n<img src=\"../../../assets/images/0006.png\" alt=\"Setup\">\r\n<br>\r\n<br>\r\n<h4 class=\"subtitle\">Objectives</h4>\r\n<ol>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Ensure switches have a basic configuration and connect as shown.\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Use the proper show commands to determine the version of STP running,\r\n    port status, and identify the Root Bridge.\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Cause a Root Port outage; determine how long it takes to converge.\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Change all switches to use RSTP test the outage again.\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Modify the bridge priority to elect S1 as the Root Bridge,\r\n    S2 as the Backup Root; diagram port results and verify your\r\n    assumptions are correct on the switch.\r\n  </li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<br>\r\n<h4><b>[1]</b> Basic configuration</h4>\r\n<hr>\r\n<ul><li>\r\n  Use <b>show cdp neighbors</b> to verify the connections (very useful\r\n  in real world setups). You can see your interface and their interface.\r\n</li></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">S1# <b>show cdp neighbors</b>\r\nCapability Codes: R - Router, T - Trans Bridge, B - Source Route Bridge\r\n                  S - Switch, H - Host, I - IGMP, r - Repeater\r\n\r\nDevice ID        Local Intrfce     Holdtme    Capability  Platform  Port ID\r\nS3               Fas 1/3            176          S I      3725      Fas 1/0\r\nS2               Fas 1/2            152          S I      3725      Fas 1/0\r\nS5               Fas 1/5            127          S I      3725      Fas 1/0\r\nS4               Fas 1/4            173          S I      3725      Fas 1/0\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<h4><b>[2]</b> Default STP verification</h4>\r\n<hr>\r\n<ul><li>\r\n  Use <b>show spanning-tree</b> to check the current config. In GNS3\r\n  we have to use <b>brief</b> to obtain a similar output (switching\r\n  doesn\'t work so well).\r\n</li></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">S1# <b>show spanning-tree brief</b>\r\nVLAN1\r\n  Spanning tree enabled protocol ieee\r\n  Root ID    Priority    32768\r\n             Address     c205.0971.0000\r\n             Cost        19\r\n             Port        46 (FastEthernet1/5)\r\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\r\n\r\n  Bridge ID  Priority    32768\r\n             Address     c207.0961.0000\r\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\r\n             Aging Time 300\r\n\r\nInterface                                   Designated\r\nName                 Port ID Prio Cost  Sts Cost  Bridge ID            Port ID\r\n-------------------- ------- ---- ----- --- ----- -------------------- -------\r\nFastEthernet1/2      128.43   128    19 BLK    19 32768 c206.0961.0000 128.41\r\nFastEthernet1/3      128.44   128    19 FWD    19 32768 c207.0961.0000 128.44\r\nFastEthernet1/4      128.45   128    19 FWD    19 32768 c207.0961.0000 128.45\r\nFastEthernet1/5      128.46   128    19 FWD     0 32768 c205.0971.0000 128.41\r\n</pre>\r\n<img src=\"../../../assets/images/0007.png\" alt=\"Show spanning tree\">\r\n<br>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Here (<b>show spanning tree</b> on a real switch) we can see:\r\n    <ul>\r\n      <li>\r\n        Protocol in use: <b>ieee</b> is the plain old Common Spanning Tree,\r\n        but in Cisco devices is PVSTP.\r\n      </li>\r\n      <li>\r\n        Information about the Root Bridge. Cost 19 means our router is not\r\n        the Root Bridge. Also shows which port we have to exit in order to\r\n        reach the Root.\r\n      </li>\r\n      <li>\r\n        Information about the local switch\r\n      </li>\r\n      <li>\r\n        Interface status: root/designated ports, port status (forwarding/blocked).\r\n      </li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    In our setup, it looks like S5 is the root. We can confirm using the\r\n    same command. In a real switch we would see all <b>Designated</b> ports.\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">S5# <b>show spanning-tree brief</b>\r\nVLAN1\r\n  Spanning tree enabled protocol ieee\r\n  Root ID    Priority    32768\r\n             Address     c205.0971.0000\r\n             This bridge is the root\r\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\r\n\r\n  Bridge ID  Priority    32768\r\n             Address     c205.0971.0000\r\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\r\n             Aging Time 300\r\n\r\nInterface                                   Designated\r\nName                 Port ID Prio Cost  Sts Cost  Bridge ID            Port ID\r\n-------------------- ------- ---- ----- --- ----- -------------------- -------\r\nFastEthernet1/0      128.41   128    19 FWD     0 32768 c205.0971.0000 128.41\r\nFastEthernet1/1      128.42   128    19 FWD     0 32768 c205.0971.0000 128.42\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<h4><b>[3]</b> Convergence after a root port outage</h4>\r\n<hr>\r\n<ul><li>\r\n  Shut down the root interface on S1.\r\n</li></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">S1(config)# <b>interface fa1/5</b>\r\nS1(config-if)# <b>shutdown</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<ul><li>\r\n  Check <b>show spanning tree</b> to see which states the new root interface\r\n  candidate goes through: <b>LIS</b> (listening), <b>LRN</b> (learning) and\r\n  <b>FWD</b> (forward).\r\n</li></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">S1# <b>show spanning-tree brief</b>\r\nVLAN1\r\n  Spanning tree enabled protocol ieee\r\n  Root ID    Priority    32768\r\n             Address     c205.0971.0000\r\n             Cost        38\r\n             Port        43 (FastEthernet1/2)\r\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\r\n\r\n  Bridge ID  Priority    32768\r\n             Address     c207.0961.0000\r\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\r\n             Aging Time 300\r\n\r\nInterface                                   Designated\r\nName                 Port ID Prio Cost  Sts Cost  Bridge ID            Port ID\r\n-------------------- ------- ---- ----- --- ----- -------------------- -------\r\nFastEthernet1/2      128.43   128    19 LIS    19 32768 c206.0961.0000 128.41\r\nFastEthernet1/3      128.44   128    19 FWD    38 32768 c207.0961.0000 128.44\r\nFastEthernet1/4      128.45   128    19 FWD    38 32768 c207.0961.0000 128.45\r\n</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">S1# <b>show spanning-tree brief</b>\r\nVLAN1\r\n  Spanning tree enabled protocol ieee\r\n  Root ID    Priority    32768\r\n             Address     c205.0971.0000\r\n             Cost        38\r\n             Port        43 (FastEthernet1/2)\r\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\r\n\r\n  Bridge ID  Priority    32768\r\n             Address     c207.0961.0000\r\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\r\n             Aging Time 300\r\n\r\nInterface                                   Designated\r\nName                 Port ID Prio Cost  Sts Cost  Bridge ID            Port ID\r\n-------------------- ------- ---- ----- --- ----- -------------------- -------\r\nFastEthernet1/2      128.43   128    19 LRN    19 32768 c206.0961.0000 128.41\r\nFastEthernet1/3      128.44   128    19 FWD    38 32768 c207.0961.0000 128.44\r\nFastEthernet1/4      128.45   128    19 FWD    38 32768 c207.0961.0000 128.45\r\n</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">S1# <b>show spanning-tree brief</b>\r\nVLAN1\r\n  Spanning tree enabled protocol ieee\r\n  Root ID    Priority    32768\r\n             Address     c205.0971.0000\r\n             Cost        38\r\n             Port        43 (FastEthernet1/2)\r\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\r\n\r\n  Bridge ID  Priority    32768\r\n             Address     c207.0961.0000\r\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\r\n             Aging Time 300\r\n\r\nInterface                                   Designated\r\nName                 Port ID Prio Cost  Sts Cost  Bridge ID            Port ID\r\n-------------------- ------- ---- ----- --- ----- -------------------- -------\r\nFastEthernet1/2      128.43   128    19 FWD    19 32768 c206.0961.0000 128.41\r\nFastEthernet1/3      128.44   128    19 FWD    38 32768 c207.0961.0000 128.44\r\nFastEthernet1/4      128.45   128    19 FWD    38 32768 c207.0961.0000 128.45\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Each of this states has a fixed time in STP. The total time is 30sec:\r\n    <ul>\r\n      <li>\r\n        LIS (listening): 15 seconds. It\'s listening for BPDUs from other\r\n        switches in the network.\r\n      </li>\r\n      <li>\r\n        LRN (learning): 15 seconds. It\'s learning MAC addresses. This gives the\r\n        switch time to learn how the network looks like.\r\n      </li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br>\r\n<h4><b>[4]</b> RSTP</h4>\r\n<hr>\r\n<ul><li>\r\n  RSTP doesn\'t work in GNS3, but this would be the command to enable it on\r\n  real switches (we should do it on all of them):\r\n</li></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">S1(config)# <b>spanning-tree mode rapid-pvst</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>\r\n      In a normal switch we would see <b>Spanning tree enabled protocol rstp</b>\r\n      in the output of the <b>show spanning-tree</b> command.\r\n    </li>\r\n    <li>\r\n      This protocol takes about 2sec to converge. Normal spanning tree is passive,\r\n      and rapid spanning tree is active.\r\n    </li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br>\r\n<h4><b>[4]</b> Manually assigning the Root Bridge</h4>\r\n<hr>\r\n<ul><li>\r\n  Remember that Cisco uses PVSTP so we need to specify the VLAN. We can have\r\n  different root bridges for different VLANs.\r\n</li></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">S1(config)# <b>spanning-tree vlan 1 priority 4096</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">S2(config)# <b>spanning-tree vlan 1 priority 8192</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    The final status of the network:\r\n  </li>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>\r\n      All <b>S1</b> ports will be forwarding (they are designated ports)\r\n    </li>\r\n    <li>\r\n      All <b>S2</b> ports will be in forwarding state as well. But only the one\r\n      connected to <b>S1</b> will be actually working.\r\n    </li>\r\n    <li>\r\n      Why? Because he is the switch with the lowest ID among the remaining. Those links\r\n      won\'t work because they will be blocked on the other end.\r\n    </li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">S1# <b>show spanning-tree brief</b>\r\nVLAN1\r\n  Spanning tree enabled protocol ieee\r\n  Root ID    Priority    4096\r\n             Address     c202.0d53.0000\r\n             This bridge is the root\r\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\r\n\r\n  Bridge ID  Priority    4096\r\n             Address     c202.0d53.0000\r\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\r\n             Aging Time 300\r\n\r\nInterface                                   Designated\r\nName                 Port ID Prio Cost  Sts Cost  Bridge ID            Port ID\r\n-------------------- ------- ---- ----- --- ----- -------------------- -------\r\nFastEthernet1/2      128.43   128    19 FWD     0  4096 c202.0d53.0000 128.43\r\nFastEthernet1/3      128.44   128    19 FWD     0  4096 c202.0d53.0000 128.44\r\nFastEthernet1/4      128.45   128    19 FWD     0  4096 c202.0d53.0000 128.45\r\nFastEthernet1/5      128.46   128    19 FWD     0  4096 c202.0d53.0000 128.46\r\n</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">S2# <b>show spanning-tree brief</b>\r\nVLAN1\r\n  Spanning tree enabled protocol ieee\r\n  Root ID    Priority    4096\r\n             Address     c202.0d53.0000\r\n             Cost        19\r\n             Port        41 (FastEthernet1/0)\r\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\r\n\r\n  Bridge ID  Priority    8192\r\n             Address     c201.0d53.0000\r\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\r\n             Aging Time 300\r\n\r\nInterface                                   Designated\r\nName                 Port ID Prio Cost  Sts Cost  Bridge ID            Port ID\r\n-------------------- ------- ---- ----- --- ----- -------------------- -------\r\nFastEthernet1/0      128.41   128    19 FWD     0  4096 c202.0d53.0000 128.43\r\nFastEthernet1/3      128.44   128    19 FWD    19  8192 c201.0d53.0000 128.44\r\nFastEthernet1/4      128.45   128    19 FWD    19  8192 c201.0d53.0000 128.45\r\nFastEthernet1/5      128.46   128    19 FWD    19  8192 c201.0d53.0000 128.46\r\n</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">S3# <b>show spanning-tree brief</b>\r\nVLAN1\r\n  Spanning tree enabled protocol ieee\r\n  Root ID    Priority    4096\r\n             Address     c202.0d53.0000\r\n             Cost        19\r\n             Port        41 (FastEthernet1/0)\r\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\r\n\r\n  Bridge ID  Priority    32768\r\n             Address     c200.0d53.0000\r\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\r\n             Aging Time 300\r\n\r\nInterface                                   Designated\r\nName                 Port ID Prio Cost  Sts Cost  Bridge ID            Port ID\r\n-------------------- ------- ---- ----- --- ----- -------------------- -------\r\nFastEthernet1/0      128.41   128    19 FWD     0  4096 c202.0d53.0000 128.44\r\nFastEthernet1/1      128.42   128    19 BLK    19  8192 c201.0d53.0000 128.44\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n', '2018-01-30 08:49:13'),
(13, 'CBTNuggets STP Portfast/BPDUGuard Lab', 6, '<style>\r\n</style>\r\n<!--<img src=\"../../../assets/images/00setup.png\" alt=\"Setup\">-->\r\n<h4 class=\"subtitle\">Setup</h4>\r\n<img src=\"../../../assets/images/0008.png\" alt=\"Setup\">\r\n<br>\r\n<br>\r\n<h4 class=\"subtitle\">Objectives</h4>\r\n<ol>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Configure Portfast on all non-trunking ports of Dr. Evil.\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Ensure Dr. Evil is indeed the STP Root Bridge of the network.\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Protect Dr. Evil from other managed devices by correctly configuring\r\n    BPDUGuard.\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Ensure BPDUGuard is working correctly - connect switch Mini-Me to the\r\n    network and ensure appropiate action is taken.\r\n  </li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<br>\r\n<h4><b>[1, 2]</b> Root bridge and Portfast configuration</h4>\r\n<hr>\r\n<ul><li>\r\n  Let\'s make sure Dr Evil is the root bridge first\r\n</li></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">DrEvil(config)# <b>spanning-tree vlan 1 root primary</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<ul><ul><li>\r\n  This command tells the switch \"look around, see what else is out there,\r\n  and set your priority lower than everything else\".\r\n</li></ul></ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">DrEvil(config)# <b>int range fa1/0 - 15</b>\r\nDrEvil(config-if-range)# <b>spanning-tree portfast</b>\r\n%Warning: portfast should only be enabled on ports connected to a single host.\r\n Connecting hubs, concentrators, switches,  bridges, etc.to this interface\r\n when portfast is enabled, can cause temporary spanning tree loops.\r\n Use with CAUTION\r\n\r\n!One line for each interface...\r\n\r\n%Portfast has been configured on FastEthernet1/15 but will only\r\n have effect when the interface is in a non-trunking mode.\r\n</pre>\r\n<ul><ul><li>\r\n  For security reasons, the portfast config will only work when the interface\r\n  is connected to an end device (it will shutdown in case it receives attempts\r\n  of trunking negotiation)\r\n</li></ul></ul>\r\n<br>\r\n<h4><b>[3]</b> BPDUGuard configuration</h4>\r\n<hr>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    On some switches we can activate it like this:\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">DrEvil(config)# <b>int range fa1/0 - 15</b>\r\nDrEvil(config-if-range)# <b>spanning-tree portfast bpduguard</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    On some other versions:\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\">DrEvil(config)# <b>int range fa1/0 - 15</b>\r\nDrEvil(config-if-range)# <b>spanning-tree bpduguard enable</b>\r\n</pre>\r\n<br>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    When the BPDUGuard is activated, the switch thinks \"if I see a BPDU coming\r\n    in, I\'m going to turn off the interface\"\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Interface will go in an <b>err-disable</b> status. We can check this in\r\n    <b>show interfaces fa1/0</b>.\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    We would need to do <b>shutdown</b> + <b>no shutdown</b> on that interface.\r\n  <li>\r\n    In GNS3, BPDUGuard doesn\'t work, so no examples.\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '2018-02-01 09:18:33'),
(14, 'Git essentials', 7, '<style>\r\n</style>\r\n<!--<img src=\"../../../assets/images/00setup.png\" alt=\"Setup\">-->\r\n<h4 class=\"subtitle\">Basic workflow</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    A git project has 3 parts:\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[...]\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Clone the repo\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#4E9A06\"><b>user@ubuntupc</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~/GitTest</b></font>$ git clone https://cyberFELIX@bitbucket.org/cyberFELIX/felix-test-repo.git\r\nCloning into &apos;felix-test-repo&apos;...\r\nPassword for &apos;https://cyberFELIX@bitbucket.org&apos;:\r\nremote: Counting objects: 3, done.\r\nremote: Compressing objects: 100% (2/2), done.\r\nremote: Total 3 (delta 0), reused 0 (delta 0)\r\nUnpacking objects: 100% (3/3), done.\r\n</pre>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Add a new file and check the status of the repository\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#4E9A06\"><b>user@ubuntupc</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~/GitTest/felix-test-repo</b></font>$ git status\r\nOn branch master\r\nYour branch is up to date with &apos;origin/master&apos;.\r\n\r\nUntracked files:\r\n  (use &quot;git add &lt;file&gt;...&quot; to include in what will be committed)\r\n\r\n	<font color=\"#CC0000\">index.js</font>\r\n\r\nnothing added to commit but untracked files present (use &quot;git add&quot; to track)\r\n</pre>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Send the new file to the staging area\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#4E9A06\"><b>user@ubuntupc</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~/GitTest/felix-test-repo</b></font>$ git add .\r\n</pre>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Modify the file and show differences between the staging area and\r\n    the working directory\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#4E9A06\"><b>user@ubuntupc</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~/GitTest/felix-test-repo</b></font>$ echo &quot;var newVar = 7&quot; &gt;&gt; index.js\r\n<font color=\"#4E9A06\"><b>user@ubuntupc</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~/GitTest/felix-test-repo</b></font>$ git diff\r\n<b>diff --git a/index.js b/index.js</b>\r\n<b>index 7921bd9..ea3cfaf 100644</b>\r\n<b>--- a/index.js</b>\r\n<b>+++ b/index.js</b>\r\n<font color=\"#06989A\">@@ -1 +1,2 @@</font>\r\n var hola = &apos;hello&apos;\r\n<font color=\"#4E9A06\">+var newVar = 7</font>\r\n</pre>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Commit: permanently store the changes from the staging area inside the\r\n    repository.\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#4E9A06\"><b>user@ubuntupc</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~/GitTest/felix-test-repo</b></font>$ git add .\r\n<font color=\"#4E9A06\"><b>user@ubuntupc</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~/GitTest/felix-test-repo</b></font>$ git commit -m &quot;First modifications&quot;\r\n[master c48a54d] First modifications\r\n 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+)\r\n create mode 100644 index.js\r\n</pre>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    See the list of commits.\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#4E9A06\"><b>user@ubuntupc</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~/GitTest/felix-test-repo</b></font>$ git log\r\n<font color=\"#C4A000\">commit c48a54d89b2ff4310ff4d41fb8d3bd85daa54b6e (</font><font color=\"#06989A\"><b>HEAD -&gt; </b></font><font color=\"#4E9A06\"><b>master</b></font><font color=\"#C4A000\">)</font>\r\nAuthor: d-silvas &lt;d.silvas@outlook.com&gt;\r\nDate:   Fri Feb 2 12:56:00 2018 +0000\r\n\r\n    First modifications\r\n\r\n<font color=\"#C4A000\">commit 36d6a86a64ee49ba6e10b3e6a5360006a5ff93dd (</font><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>origin/master</b></font><font color=\"#C4A000\">, </font><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>origin/HEAD</b></font><font color=\"#C4A000\">)</font>\r\nAuthor: David Silva &lt;felix@cyberratss.london&gt;\r\nDate:   Fri Feb 2 12:33:57 2018 +0000\r\n\r\n    README.md created online with Bitbucket\r\n</pre>\r\n', '2018-02-03 22:34:25');

